citizens from
negotiating with foreign
governments when

20:38.804 --> 20:44.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they're not in power, when
they're not yet
in a position to do so in the
United States.

20:44.276 --> 20:48.848 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And every indication to us is
that Flynn did
just that in this conversation.

20:48.881 --> 20:52.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is that the
reason that
Vladimir Putin didn't retaliate
once those

20:52.918 --> 20:54.120 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
sanctions came out?

20:54.153 --> 20:56.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It seemed that there was about a
24-hour gap
or so there.

20:56.555 --> 21:02.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GREG MILLER: Yes, I mean, that
was this huge
source of concern and surprise
and mystery.

21:02.394 --> 21:09.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, in the history of
U.S.-Russia relationships,
there have been lots of
retaliatory measures,

21:09.168 --> 21:14.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
diplomatic sanctions, economic
sanctions,
expulsions of spies and so
forth.

21:14.240 --> 21:15.975 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's almost always reciprocal.

21:16.008 --> 21:19.411 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But in this case, Putin
surprised everybody
by saying, you know what, we're
not going

21:19.445 --> 21:23.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to do anything this time, we're
not going
to respond, we're just going to
wait and see

21:23.149 --> 21:24.250 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
how this plays out.

21:24.283 --> 21:26.919 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And that led to a lot of
suspicion in the
government.

21:26.952 --> 21:28.854 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Was there a signal sent?

21:28.888 --> 21:33.792 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
That led to further
investigation and scrutiny
of these calls between Flynn and
the ambassador.

21:33.826 --> 21:39.231 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: If now
Congress or anyone
decides to take actions against
Mike Flynn,

21:39.265 --> 21:41.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is there the possibility of a
chilling effect?

21:41.367 --> 21:43.335 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Diplomats talk to each other all
the time.

21:43.369 --> 21:45.938 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have relationships that
span beyond administrations.

21:45.971 --> 21:48.874 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They meet each other in
different conferences
and so forth.

21:48.908 --> 21:49.875 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GREG MILLER: Absolutely.

21:49.909 --> 21:51.343 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, that is an issue.

21:51.377 --> 21:55.281 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that probably helps explain
why this law
has never been prosecuted.

21:55.314 --> 22:02.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Authorities, U.S. authorities,
do not really
want to discourage people who
are supposed

22:02.154 --> 22:05.324 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
to be communicating with
officials overseas
from doing so.

22:05.357 --> 22:10.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, you're not supposed to
send signals
like this that undermine the
existing government,

22:10.696 --> 22:13.399 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that are contrary to the U.S.
policy.

22:13.432 --> 22:19.071 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And in this case, it was
particularly egregious,
because this was at a moment
when the United

22:19.104 --> 22:23.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
States was just coming to the
grips with the
fact that Russia had waged a
cyber-campaign

22:23.209 --> 22:28.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to upend the 2016 election and
try to help
elect Trump.

22:28.047 --> 22:32.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And here his top national
security adviser
is communicating with the
Russian ambassador

22:32.551 --> 22:36.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in that very moment in time and
apparently
sending a signal, don't worry
about this.

22:36.956 --> 22:40.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Greg Miller of
The Washington Post, thanks so
much.

22:40.392 --> 22:42.228 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GREG MILLER: Thank you.

22:42.261 --> 22:45.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, after Hari
recorded that
conversation, President Trump
was asked about

22:46.031 --> 22:48.467 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the story while flying to
Florida.

22:48.500 --> 22:50.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mr. Trump said -- quote -- "I
don't know about
it.

22:51.003 --> 22:52.204 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I haven't seen it.

22:52.238 --> 22:54.206 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What report is that?"

22:54.240 --> 23:04.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
National Security Adviser
Michael Flynn was
among the passengers on Air
Force One.

23:04.350 --> 23:10.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
National Security Adviser
Michael Flynn was
among the passengers on Air
Force One.

23:10.489 --> 23:12.224 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Stay with us.

23:12.258 --> 23:15.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
Mark Shields
and David Brooks' take on the
week's news;

23:15.628 --> 23:20.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
plus, Smokey Robinson reflects
on his lifelong
contribution to music.

23:20.766 --> 23:26.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: The president gets a
key member
of his Cabinet confirmed, a
right-hand man

23:26.705 --> 23:31.877 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
who will take aim at the
Affordable Care Act,
and will serve as the country's
top health

23:31.910 --> 23:32.878 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
official.

23:32.911 --> 23:34.713 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Lisa Desjardins has the story.

23:34.747 --> 23:41.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: He is, after
his swearing-in
today, the nation's 23rd
secretary of health

23:41.353 --> 23:44.523 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and human services.

23:44.556 --> 23:49.728 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. Senate confirmed
Georgia Congressman
Tom Price in the wee hours this
morning on

23:49.762 --> 23:53.532 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a party-line vote of 52-47.

23:53.565 --> 23:57.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Secretary Price is a longtime
opponent of
the Affordable Care Act.

23:57.236 --> 24:01.006 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To Democrats like Maria Cantwell
of Washington
State, that is the problem.

24:01.040 --> 24:02.775 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

24:02.808 --> 24:05.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARIA CANTWELL (D), Washington:
My view is,
this vote is the first vote in
the repeal

24:05.077 --> 24:06.812 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the Affordable Care Act.

24:06.845 --> 24:10.749 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: But to
Republicans like Tom
Cotton of Arkansas, that's
Price's appeal.

24:10.783 --> 24:12.584 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

24:12.618 --> 24:14.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOM COTTON (R), Arkansas: You
could say his
chief qualification for the job
of replacing

24:14.620 --> 24:18.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obamacare is, he had the good
sense to oppose
it in the first place.

24:18.390 --> 24:23.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Price is also a
retired doctor,
the first physician to lead HHS
in nearly

24:23.729 --> 24:26.165 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
25 years.

24:26.198 --> 24:30.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in confirmation hearings, he
faced tough
questions over his relationship
with health

24:30.536 --> 24:36.408 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
care companies, and his
investment in some
which were affected by his
actions in Congress.

24:36.442 --> 24:41.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now Price is responsible for a
more than a
trillion-dollar health agency
budget, for

24:41.647 --> 24:46.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a department that oversees food
and drugs,
biomedical research, public
health threats,

24:46.385 --> 24:50.556 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and, of course, a large portion
of U.S. health
care.

24:50.589 --> 24:55.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That includes Medicaid, which
covers more
than 74 million people, and
Medicare, over

24:55.527 --> 24:57.429 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
55 million.

24:57.463 --> 24:58.430 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
His theme?

24:58.464 --> 25:00.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A smaller role for the federal
government.

25:00.799 --> 25:05.671 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Congress, Price backed a
proposed cap on
Medicare spending per person.

25:05.704 --> 25:10.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Price also supported giving
states fixed amounts,
in block grants, to cover
low-income people

25:10.809 --> 25:12.478 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on Medicaid.

25:12.511 --> 25:16.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But his new boss, Donald Trump,
said on the
campaign trail he wouldn't touch
Medicare

25:16.949 --> 25:18.751 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or Medicaid.

25:18.784 --> 25:22.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP, President of the
United States:
Save Medicare, Medicaid, and
Social Security

25:22.721 --> 25:24.089 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
without cuts.

25:24.123 --> 25:25.924 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Have to do it.

25:25.958 --> 25:29.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Mr. Trump has
not commented
since becoming president, but he
has stressed

25:29.094 --> 25:33.432 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an area of agreement with Price:
repeal of
the Affordable Care Act.

25:33.465 --> 25:37.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This was today at a joint press
conference
with Japanese Prime Minister
Shinzo Abe.

25:37.369 --> 25:40.739 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: Obamacare, as you
know, is a
total and complete disaster.

25:40.773 --> 25:48.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we're going to end up with
tremendous
health care at a lower price,
and I think

25:48.313 --> 25:50.048 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
people are going to be extremely
happy.

25:50.082 --> 25:54.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Meantime, the
Associated
Press estimates some 12 million
Americans

25:54.286 --> 25:58.791 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
have signed up for the
Affordable Care Act
for the next year, and
Republicans are feeling

25:58.824 --> 26:01.760 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the pressure from many concerned
about a replacement.

26:01.794 --> 26:08.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last night at a town hall
advertised as focused
as health care, Utah Congressman
Jason Chaffetz

26:08.734 --> 26:12.337 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
was bombarded by angry
constituents on a variety
of issues.

26:12.371 --> 26:18.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in Tennessee, a similar
scene for Representative
Diane Black, as health care
policy and politics

26:18.844 --> 26:20.913 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
collide.

26:20.946 --> 26:24.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now that Secretary Price has
been sworn in,
let's take a closer look at what
he may try

26:25.017 --> 26:28.420 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to do, more quickly, and over
the long term.

26:28.454 --> 26:30.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Julie Rovner covers this for
Kaiser Health
News.

26:30.789 --> 26:31.824 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She's a friend of the
"NewsHour."

26:31.857 --> 26:32.825 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And she joins me now.

26:32.858 --> 26:33.826 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thank you, Julie.

26:33.859 --> 26:35.594 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JULIE ROVNER, Kaiser Health
News: Thank you.

26:35.627 --> 26:36.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Let's talk with
Republican
agenda item number one, the
Affordable Care

26:36.962 --> 26:38.564 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Act.

26:38.597 --> 26:41.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Secretary Price, we have a
man who literally
authored a bill to repeal it.

26:41.867 --> 26:46.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have both reported that
Republicans see
him as a major part of their
repeal effort.

26:46.371 --> 26:47.840 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But what can he actually do?

26:47.873 --> 26:50.442 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is he likely to do on the
Affordable
Care Act?

26:50.476 --> 26:54.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JULIE ROVNER: Well, what he can
actually do
and what he will likely do are
two different

26:54.480 --> 26:55.447 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
things.

26:55.481 --> 26:57.316 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What he can actually do is quite
a lot.

26:57.349 --> 27:00.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For as long as the Affordable
Care Act was,
there are a whole lot of places
where it says

27:00.352 --> 27:02.554 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the secretary shall or the
secretary may.

27:02.588 --> 27:07.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So he has a lot of power to
determine the
details around what happens to
the law.

27:07.259 --> 27:11.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he can take apart a lot of
the details
that the Obama administration
added to it.

27:11.797 --> 27:13.565 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Now, what will he do?

27:13.599 --> 27:16.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's an issue here with
whether or not
the Republicans want to make
sure that there

27:16.935 --> 27:22.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is still an individual insurance
market next
year in 2018, while they're
figuring out what

27:22.040 --> 27:23.609 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to replace it with.

27:23.642 --> 27:26.478 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Insurers need to know that
really by later
this spring.

27:26.512 --> 27:30.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so some are expecting him
to, on the one
hand, try to take some things
apart, on the

27:30.849 --> 27:35.721 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
other hand, try to make sure
that the insurance
industry stays in, and so to
give them some

27:35.754 --> 27:37.489 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
security about what might be
coming.

27:37.523 --> 27:41.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: And as he has
to deal with
the insurance market, which is
one issue,

27:41.527 --> 27:44.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he has to deal with, of course,
all of us
and our health care.

27:44.596 --> 27:47.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And Obamacare has some
preventative services
in it.

27:47.699 --> 27:50.736 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Included in that, contraception,
screenings.

27:50.769 --> 27:54.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What kind of say does he have
over whether
those will continue to be
cost-free?

27:54.706 --> 27:57.910 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JULIE ROVNER: Well, he can
change that if
he wants to.

27:57.943 --> 28:00.178 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now, some of it was done by
regulation.

28:00.212 --> 28:05.183 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And in order to change
regulations, there
is a process that even
departments have to

28:05.217 --> 28:07.819 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
go through of notice and public
comment.

28:07.853 --> 28:10.389 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it can take several, many
months sometimes.

28:10.422 --> 28:14.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is also something that's a
little less
formal called guidance, and
guidance, he can

28:14.626 --> 28:16.929 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
undo pretty much whenever he
wants.

28:16.962 --> 28:18.864 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, he has the power both ways.

28:18.897 --> 28:20.899 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's just whether some things
will be faster
or slower.

28:20.933 --> 28:23.335 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: On
contraception, a lot of
people paying attention to that.

28:23.368 --> 28:25.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is one that could take a
few months,
but he could still do it?

28:25.837 --> 28:27.673 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Is that right?

28:27.706 --> 28:29.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JULIE ROVNER: Yes, well, he can
make it easier
probably for religious
organizations, employers

28:29.841 --> 28:32.778 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to opt out of providing
contraception.

28:32.811 --> 28:34.580 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's been a huge issue.

28:34.613 --> 28:37.816 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In terms of keeping it
cost-free, that would
have to be changed through a
regulation.

28:37.849 --> 28:39.251 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That would take a little bit
longer.

28:39.284 --> 28:42.087 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Another one,
Medicaid.

28:42.120 --> 28:45.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Republicans on the Hill, I know,
tell both
of us that that is one of the
biggest puzzles

28:45.190 --> 28:46.658 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for them.

28:46.692 --> 28:49.895 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have to deal with how to
expand it or
not expand it, what they do.

28:49.928 --> 28:54.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, Secretary Price, you report
that he can
change requirements for the poor
who receive

28:54.399 --> 28:55.367 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Medicaid?

28:55.400 --> 28:57.135 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JULIE ROVNER: That's right.

28:57.169 --> 28:59.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, he can't change the law,
but he can
change some of the regulations
that have to

28:59.571 --> 29:02.774 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
do with who gets it, with who
gets much.

29:02.808 --> 29:07.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Of course, Congress is talking
about turning
Medicaid into a block grant,
which would limit

29:07.245 --> 29:10.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
how much money states could get,
although
they would have much more
flexibility.

29:10.716 --> 29:15.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He could through his own power
give states
a lot more flexibility than they
have now,

29:15.654 --> 29:17.756 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
which is what many are expecting
him to do.

29:17.789 --> 29:22.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So things like requiring people
on Medicaid
to meet a work requirement,
that's something

29:22.427 --> 29:26.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the Obama administration
resisted, but
that new Secretary Price might
not.

29:26.632 --> 29:29.701 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That's an old
