Is there one standard for women
and another
for men?

38:59.304 --> 39:04.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Men aren't responsible, multiple
millionaire
men who deal in minimum wage
jobs, who deal

39:04.509 --> 39:08.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in undocumented immigrants
working for them
at reduced wages?

39:08.780 --> 39:11.349 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I think these are fights
worth making.

39:11.382 --> 39:13.618 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, what about
that, David?

39:13.651 --> 39:17.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because some people are looking
at Washington
and saying, oh, it's just more
of the same,

39:17.322 --> 39:21.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the wheels are not turning in
the nation's
capital.

39:21.159 --> 39:24.362 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Well, that's
patently true.

39:24.395 --> 39:30.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the various nominees, I
generally think
the president should get his
Cabinet picks,

39:30.568 --> 39:34.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
unless they're egregiously out
of the range,
either ethically or
intellectually out of

39:34.706 --> 39:36.808 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the range of what's acceptable.

39:36.841 --> 39:40.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I have to say a lot of these
nominees
are not necessarily my cup of
tea, but I think

39:41.012 --> 39:42.814 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they're clearly within the
range.

39:42.847 --> 39:48.086 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Jeff Sessions has some
problematic spots on
his history, but he has been a
pretty normal,

39:48.119 --> 39:51.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
respectable senator, more
conservative than
a lot of us, but a respectable
senator for

39:51.789 --> 39:53.591 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a long period of time.

39:53.625 --> 39:56.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, one could -- I think the
Democrats are
right to protest, but I don't
think he's so

39:57.028 --> 39:59.764 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
far out of the range of normalcy
that he shouldn't
be confirmed.

39:59.797 --> 40:03.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Betsy DeVos is not the most
informed person
on education policy, but I have
seen her present

40:03.901 --> 40:09.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a few times, and she presents as
a pretty
respectable, intelligent person
who has cared

40:09.507 --> 40:12.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
passionately about education and
cares about
charter schools.

40:12.477 --> 40:17.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The teachers union may not like
her, but she's
clearly within the range of
Republican policy-makers.

40:17.282 --> 40:20.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As for multimillionaires, a lot
of us hope
to be a multimillionaire some
day.

40:21.019 --> 40:24.656 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Again, spotty records, but it
seems to be
not without the range.

40:24.689 --> 40:26.157 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't blame the Democrats for
fighting.

40:26.190 --> 40:29.060 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have got a very energized
base.

40:29.093 --> 40:31.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there is a lot to complain
about a lot
of these nominees.

40:31.929 --> 40:36.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think, if you are actually
going to
turn someone down from a
president's own Cabinet,

40:36.334 --> 40:39.370 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
it better be a lot more
egregious than the
cases we have seen.

40:39.404 --> 40:41.139 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, that's my
question, Mark.

40:41.172 --> 40:42.273 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Where draw the line?

40:42.307 --> 40:43.441 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Where should Democrats say no?

40:43.474 --> 40:45.977 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Well, they have
drawn the line,
Judy.

40:46.010 --> 40:48.646 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have confirmed -- Tillerson
is confirmed.

40:48.680 --> 40:49.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They backed Mattis.

40:49.847 --> 40:51.649 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're not going to fight Ben
Carson.

40:51.683 --> 40:53.718 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think these -- I disagree with
David.

40:53.751 --> 40:58.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I agree with his assumption and
his premise
that a president is entitled to
a Cabinet,

40:58.589 --> 41:00.758 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
obviously, but it's not a rubber
stamp.

41:00.792 --> 41:05.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I don't think anybody could
watch the
confirmation hearings of Betsy
DeVos and say

41:05.963 --> 41:09.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that this is somebody qualified
to be secretary
of education.

41:09.367 --> 41:12.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ninety percent of children in
America go to
public schools.

41:12.603 --> 41:16.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She knows nothing about public
schools and
apparently cares less.

41:16.607 --> 41:21.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And her position on guns in
schools, got to
-- for potential grizzlies, we
should have

41:21.946 --> 41:23.848 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
guns available in schools?

41:23.881 --> 41:31.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Andrew Puzder, this is
somebody who basically
has just broken the law, and
he's going to

41:31.489 --> 41:35.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be held to no standard at all,
whereas women
nominees have been rejected in
the past.

41:35.827 --> 41:40.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I think even
Republicans are
saying Puzder may have a
problem.

41:41.032 --> 41:43.368 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
David, what about the point that
Mark is making?

41:43.401 --> 41:44.736 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Well, in some
cases, I agree.

41:44.769 --> 41:47.071 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On the Puzder point, I do agree
there has
been a double standard.

41:47.105 --> 41:52.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the DeVos case, I agree that
the gun -- her
gun position is kind of weird,
kind of crazy,

41:52.844 --> 41:54.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but I do think she does know
about public
schools.

41:54.912 --> 42:00.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The reason the Betsy DeVos case
was the centerpiece
case for the Democrats wasn't
about her weakness

42:00.118 --> 42:03.121 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as a knowledgeable person on
education policy.

42:03.154 --> 42:05.189 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She does care about charter
schools, which
are public schools.

42:05.223 --> 42:08.893 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She does care about choice,
which is a perfectly
legitimate thing to care about.

42:08.926 --> 42:12.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's because it's the one issue
where the
Democratic donor base was really
energized,

42:12.296 --> 42:14.232 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
which was the teacher unions.

42:14.265 --> 42:17.702 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People ask, quite legitimately,
why DeVos
and why not a lot of the others?

42:17.735 --> 42:21.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it's because it has to do
with the special
interest groups that run a lot
of Washington.

42:21.272 --> 42:23.141 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Would she be my first pick?

42:23.174 --> 42:24.409 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
No.

42:24.442 --> 42:27.745 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is she someone who has dedicated
her life
to education policy?

42:27.779 --> 42:29.680 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Yes, actually, she has.

42:29.714 --> 42:31.282 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have seen her present a few
times.

42:31.315 --> 42:32.917 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I don't really know her.

42:32.950 --> 42:36.954 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I have seen her present on
education policy,
and she's not a stupid person.

42:36.988 --> 42:40.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's quite a smart person,
capable, pretty
sophisticated in subtle thought.

42:40.224 --> 42:43.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so to me, that puts her in
the realm of
policy.

42:43.094 --> 42:46.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we're in a climate where, as
today, she
tries to visit a school, and she
can't even

42:46.097 --> 42:49.267 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
do that because protesters are
blocking that.

42:49.300 --> 42:54.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's what I mean about the
rising tide
of incivility that's sweeping
over politics.

42:54.705 --> 42:56.240 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: That was wrong.

42:56.274 --> 42:58.309 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She should have been allowed to
go in a public
school.

42:58.342 --> 43:00.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It would have been a novel
experience for
her.

43:00.311 --> 43:01.646 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

43:01.679 --> 43:03.448 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: And this is not
about the teachers
unions alone.

43:03.481 --> 43:08.686 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
That's a very convenient
punching bag, to
say that Democrats are just
jumping at strings.

43:08.719 --> 43:13.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yes, the teachers unions opposed
her, and
for good reason.

43:13.057 --> 43:17.328 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They don't think that her
commitment to public
education exists.

43:17.361 --> 43:19.931 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So -- you know, but they're not
simply responding.

43:19.964 --> 43:26.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have confirmed all sorts of
Republican
secretaries of education in the
past who favored

43:26.204 --> 43:28.473 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
choice, including Lamar
Alexander.

43:28.506 --> 43:31.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: David, you want a
final 20
seconds here?

43:31.876 --> 43:33.144 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

43:33.177 --> 43:37.048 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: No, I'm willing to
respect Mark's
disagreement.

43:37.081 --> 43:38.850 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're not going to be like the
rest of the
country.

43:38.883 --> 43:42.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right, well,
we have a
little bit of comity in the
United States

43:42.720 --> 43:44.689 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tonight right here, right here
on the "NewsHour."

43:44.722 --> 43:49.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: What is Donald
Trump going to
give President Putin for
Valentine's Day?

43:49.660 --> 43:50.628 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm interested.

43:50.661 --> 43:51.629 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

43:51.662 --> 43:53.397 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Maybe David's got
an idea.

43:53.431 --> 43:55.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We will know by
next Friday,
because Valentine's Day is
Tuesday, in case

43:55.833 --> 43:57.702 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the two of you have forgotten.

43:57.735 --> 44:11.549 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mark Shields, David Brooks,
thank you.

44:11.582 --> 44:16.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Finally tonight: Motown legend
Smokey Robinson
and the music he's made popular
for decades.

44:16.854 --> 44:20.725 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He is the focus of a special
tonight on PBS.

44:20.758 --> 44:25.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown sat down with him
on the eve
of getting a major honor to see
how he continues

44:25.696 --> 44:31.636 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to make what is old new again.

44:31.669 --> 44:44.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: He was a huge
hit-maker, 26
top 40 songs in the 1960s, at
one of the great

44:45.016 --> 44:51.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hit machines in pop music
history, Smokey
Robinson, his group, the
Miracles, Motown,

44:51.622 --> 45:04.368 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and a string of classics, like
"You Really
Got a Hold on Me."

45:04.402 --> 45:09.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Decades later, the 76-year-old
Robinson was
feted at a concert of his music
at Washington's

45:09.941 --> 45:17.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAR Constitution Hall, as the
winner of the
Library of Congress prestigious
Gershwin Award

45:17.281 --> 45:20.151 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for lifetime contributions to
popular song.

45:20.184 --> 45:24.355 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's been, Robinson told me, a
long and amazing
journey.

45:24.388 --> 45:27.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SMOKEY ROBINSON, Musician: From
the time I
was probably 6 or so, I wanted
to be a singer.

45:27.992 --> 45:30.061 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: From the age of
6, huh?

45:30.094 --> 45:31.862 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SMOKEY ROBINSON: Yes, I always
imagined myself.

45:31.896 --> 45:35.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would stand in the mirror,
sing with the
hairbrush and all, because I
always wanted

45:35.833 --> 45:37.201 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to do that.

45:37.234 --> 45:39.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I always watched all the
variety shows
that had entertainment.

45:39.737 --> 45:41.839 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, it was always there for me.

45:41.872 --> 45:43.574 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I just didn't think it would be
possible.

45:43.608 --> 45:49.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I never dared to -- from where I
grew up,
I just didn't think that this
life, for me,

45:50.014 --> 45:51.749 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
would be possible.

45:51.782 --> 45:56.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: At the Library of
Congress,
he toured an exhibit of Motown
memorabilia

45:56.420 --> 46:02.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the place where he'd come
from, Detroit's
North End, where, quite
literally, the stars

46:02.460 --> 46:04.295 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
aligned.

46:04.328 --> 46:06.564 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SMOKEY ROBINSON: Diana Ross grew
up four doors
down the street from me, Aretha
Franklin right

46:06.597 --> 46:11.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
around the corner, you know, and
the Temptations
right across the area, I mean,
right across

46:11.669 --> 46:13.738 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the avenue, and the Four Tops.

46:13.771 --> 46:14.739 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We had Berry Gordy.

46:14.772 --> 46:15.873 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

46:15.906 --> 46:18.542 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SMOKEY ROBINSON: We had a guy
who had the
dream.

46:18.576 --> 46:23.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Gordy, still a
friend all these
years later, founded Motown,
where Robinson

46:23.080 --> 46:29.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
served as singer and leader of
the Miracles,
songwriter and producer for
other top acts,

46:29.086 --> 46:33.090 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
including the Temptations and
Marvin Gaye,
and as a record executive.

46:33.124 --> 46:39.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I read about how you were a
precocious songwriter,
and you brought 100 or more
songs to Berry

46:39.363 --> 46:42.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Gordy, and he rejected almost
all of them,
right?

46:42.700 --> 46:43.834 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SMOKEY ROBINSON: Yes.

46:43.868 --> 46:46.203 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Somehow, that
didn't discourage
you.

46:46.237 --> 46:50.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SMOKEY ROBINSON: No, it didn't
discourage
me whatsoever, because Jackie
Wilson was my

46:50.474 --> 46:52.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
number one singing idol as a kid
growing up
in Detroit.

46:52.810 --> 46:54.045 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jackie Wilson was from Detroit.

46:54.078 --> 46:55.046 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

46:55.079 --> 46:56.213 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SMOKEY ROBINSON: And I had all
of his records.

46:56.247 --> 46:59.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And all of his songs were
written by Berry
Gordy.

46:59.650 --> 47:04.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he listened to my music and
critiqued
it for me, and started to mentor
me on how

47:04.188 --> 47:06.090 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to write songs and make them
songs.

47:06.123 --> 47:08.926 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And what was that
like in those
early days of Motown?

47:08.959 --> 47:12.329 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SMOKEY ROBINSON: It was highly
energetic.

47:12.363 --> 47:21.706 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It was so energetic and
competitive and loving
and wonderful at the same time.

47:21.739 --> 47:25.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was all that, because we were
not just
stablemates.

47:25.042 --> 47:29.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We were not just some artists
who recorded
for the same label.

47:29.747 --> 47:30.748 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We were actually friends.

47:30.781 --> 47:32.349 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We were like brothers and
sisters.

47:32.383 --> 47:33.751 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We hung out.

47:33.784 --> 47:37.855 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have what we call the Motown
family, and
we have always had that.

47:37.888 --> 47:43.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Some songs come
quickly, Robinson
says, written at the piano in 25
minutes.

47:44.028 --> 47:55.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Others, like the 1979 hit
"Cruisin'" have
to simmer.

47:55.039 --> 48:00.177 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SMOKEY ROBINSON: Took five
years.

48:00.211 --> 48:01.345 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm not exaggerating that.

48:01.378 --> 48:03.114 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It took five years.

48:03.147 --> 48:07.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, if I say the
difference
between 25 minutes and five
years, I mean,

48:07.284 --> 48:11.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what does a song have to have,
what does a
Smokey Robinson song have to
have for you

48:11.455 --> 48:12.656 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to feel you have got it?

48:12.690 --> 48:13.758 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SMOKEY ROBINSON: It has to be a
song.

